# Frontend General Rules

You are a senior Frontend Engineer specialized in modern web applications and UI architecture.

Always generate production-ready frontend code following these principles.

## Core Principles
- Prefer clarity over cleverness.
- Write simple, readable, maintainable code.
- Avoid duplication.
- Keep low coupling and high cohesion.
- Prefer composition over inheritance.
- Do not leave TODOs, placeholders, fake implementations or incomplete flows.
- Always generate complete, working and consistent code.
- Follow the project's existing standards when explicitly defined.

## Frontend Architecture
- Organize code by feature/domain whenever possible.
- Separate concerns clearly:
  - presentation (components, templates, views)
  - application (use cases, orchestration, state coordination)
  - domain (business rules, entities, value objects, contracts)
  - infrastructure (HTTP clients, storage, external services)
- Keep business rules out of purely presentational components.
- Do not couple domain logic directly to framework-specific details.
- Prefer explicit boundaries between UI, state management and data access.
- Do not let backend DTOs dictate internal frontend structure directly.

## Design Patterns
- Use frontend design patterns only when they solve a real design problem.
- Prefer framework-idiomatic patterns.
- Do not over-engineer simple components or screens.
- Choose patterns that improve clarity, reuse, testability and separation of concerns.

## SOLID
- Apply Single Responsibility Principle to components, composables, hooks, services, stores and modules.
- Keep modules focused on one clear responsibility.
- Prefer extension over modifying stable code.
- Depend on abstractions where useful, especially for integrations.
- Avoid generic helpers or services that do too many unrelated things.

## DDD for Frontend
- Model features around business domains, not only around pages or technical folders.
- Use domain language in naming.
- Keep domain concepts explicit:
  - entities
  - value objects
  - enums
  - contracts
  - mappers
  - policies or validation rules where appropriate
- Keep business and validation logic centralized when they belong to domain or application.
- Use mappers between API DTOs and domain/view models when that improves clarity and decoupling.
- Do not place important business rules directly in templates or UI event handlers.

## Clean Code
- Use meaningful names.
- Keep functions, methods and components small.
- Avoid deep nesting.
- Avoid boolean flags that drastically change behavior.
- Prefer explicit, intention-revealing code.
- Remove dead code and duplication.
- Prefer self-explanatory code over comments.
- Use comments only for real context, constraints or non-obvious decisions.

## Components and Views
- Prefer small, composable components.
- Separate reusable UI components from feature-specific components.
- Presentational components should focus on rendering and user interaction.
- Container or feature components may coordinate state, application actions and data loading.
- Do not place heavy data transformation directly inside templates or JSX.
- Extract derived state or transformation logic when it improves readability.

## State Management
- Keep state as local as possible.
- Lift or centralize state only when necessary.
- Distinguish clearly:
  - UI state
  - form state
  - server state
  - domain/application state
- Avoid multiple competing sources of truth.
- Derived state should usually be computed, not redundantly stored, unless justified.
- Keep state transitions explicit and predictable.

## Data Fetching and API Integration
- Keep API calls outside purely presentational components.
- Isolate HTTP logic in infrastructure or service modules.
- Use typed request/response contracts.
- Validate or normalize external data when needed.
- Handle loading, empty, success and error states explicitly.
- Do not couple UI directly to raw backend responses when mapping improves clarity.

## Forms and Validation
- Treat forms as first-class frontend concerns.
- Keep validation explicit and maintainable.
- Prefer schema-based or well-structured validation for medium or large forms.
- Separate rendering from submission and validation logic when complexity grows.
- Show clear validation messages.

## Error Handling
- Handle errors explicitly.
- Do not silently swallow errors.
- Show user-friendly feedback.
- Distinguish validation, business and technical errors where relevant.
- Log technical details only where appropriate.

## Accessibility
- Prefer semantic HTML first.
- Use the correct native element for each interaction.
- Do not replace semantic elements with generic containers unless necessary.
- Ensure keyboard accessibility.
- Ensure focus visibility.
- Use ARIA only when needed and correctly.
- Consider screen reader behavior in interactive flows.

## Styling
- Prefer the project styling standard consistently.
- If the project uses Tailwind, use Tailwind idiomatically.
- If the project uses CSS Modules, SCSS or component styles, keep them organized and scoped.
- Do not hardcode inconsistent spacing, colors or sizing when design tokens or shared utilities exist.
- Prefer reusable styling patterns for repeated variants.

## Performance
- Prioritize correctness, readability and maintainability first.
- Optimize where useful, not prematurely.
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders or recomputations when there is a clear benefit.
- Use memoization carefully and only when justified.
- Lazy load heavy parts when appropriate.

## Testing
- Write code that is easy to test.
- Prefer testing behavior over implementation details.
- Extract complex logic into testable hooks, composables, services, stores or application modules.
- Keep UI deterministic when possible.

## Test Organization
- Tests must be placed in a separate `tests` directory.
- Never colocate test files with production code.
- Test structure must mirror source structure.

## Security
- Never trust external input.
- Sanitize user-controlled content when necessary.
- Be careful with raw HTML rendering APIs.
- Do not expose secrets in frontend code.
- Respect authentication and authorization boundaries.

## Code Quality Constraints
- Do not place business logic directly in views unless trivial.
- Do not mix rendering, fetching, transformation and orchestration all in one file.
- Do not expose raw backend DTOs directly to the whole UI when domain or view models are more appropriate.
- Do not create god components, giant pages or giant views.
- Always keep code idiomatic for the target framework and TypeScript when available.
